[FEN "2r1kb1r/1p1n1ppp/pq1p1n2/4pPB1/4P3/P1N5/1PPNQ1PP/2KR3R b k - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Sacrificing the exchange on c3 is an important idea in the Sicilian. Since this is a tactics book we'll mostly cover exchange sacs that yield an immediate and obvious advantage and will only scratch the positional ideas on the surface. To make things a bit more difficult we put in some positions in which the sacrifice is possible, but actually, a bad idea and you have to find a different solution. Let's start with a game from the 'inventor' of the positional exchange sacrifice, Petrosian, to illustrate some ideas. }
14... Rxc3 15. bxc3 d5
{ 15...Be7!?  would be the 'positional way'. Black's compensation here is typical. White's structure is heavily damaged, his king will be weak for a long time and his rooks, due to the lack of open files, don't find a lot of work. The position is roughly equal. }
16. Nb1 Nxe4
{ 16...dxe4  is the computer choice. After  17.Qc4  Nc5  18.Rhe1  Be7  19.Bxf6  gxf6=+  the position is a mess and tough to access. The machine claims a small advantage for Black. }
17. Rxd5 Nxg5
{ But this is a clear mistake. Black had to play   17...Qxb1+!  18.Kxb1  Nxc3+  19.Kb2  Nxe2  20.Re1  Be7!!  21.Bxe7  Nf4=  with an equal endgame. }
18. h4 Be7
{ The game continued with   18...Bc5?  which just loses a tempo compared to the main line. Black eventually won after a long struggle.  19.hxg5  Be3+  20.Nd2  Bxg5  21.Qd3  Qc7  22.Kd1  Bxd2  23.Kxd2  f6  24.Kc1  Nb6  25.Rd6  O-O  26.Rd1  Qc5  27.Rd8  Qxa3+  28.Kb1  h5?  29.Rxf8+  Qxf8  30.Qe4  Qe7  31.Qb4  Qc7  32.Qd6  Qxd6  33.Rxd6  Nc4  34.Rd7  b5  35.Ra7  Ne3  36.Rxa6  Nxg2  37.Kc1  h4  38.Kd2  h3  39.Ra1  Nh4  40.c4  bxc4  41.Rh1  Nxf5  42.Kc3  Nd6  43.Rxh3  Kf7  44.Rh7  f5  45.Kb4  f4  46.Kc5  f3  47.Rh1  e4-+ }
19. hxg5 Bxg5+ 20. Nd2
{ This position is a good example of what you don't want to happen after saccing on c3. As a rule of thumb when judging a positional exchange sac, it's a good idea to look at rook activity. Rooks are very strong attackers and as soon as they have targets or open files to quickly get around the board they are usually tough to restrain. Here White's rooks are very active and it's not clear which king is actually weaker. }
*

