[SetUp "1"]

{ Sacrificing a bishop or a knight on b5 is a common theme in the Najdorf and needs to be studied in detail. Be warned, it often looks better than it is. In this chapter, we show a few ideas of how White can get a crushing attack after the sacrifice and mixed in a few positions where the sacrifice would be a bad idea. Let's start with an unclear example. }
13. Bxb5
{ Essentially forced, since White already gave up his dark-squared bishop, but the resulting position isn't clear at all. }
13... axb5 14. Ndxb5 Qb8 15. Nxd6+ Kf8 16. e5
{ As a rule of thumb, this is what White should get at least! Three pawns, a king in the middle @@StartBracket@@with a castled black king the sacrifice is usually very bad@@EndBracket@@, e4-e5, and badly placed black pieces. Without any of these puzzle pieces the sacrifice usually isn't working. White's position looks impressive, but after all, he is down a piece and in a little dilemma. The usual idea with three passed pawns for a piece would be to advance them, but here White's king would probably be unhappy about that. This position is probably equal, but easier to play for Black, we believe. As soon as he untangles his pieces, he'll have a strong attack on the queenside. }
*

