[SetUp "1"]

{ This position is not only famous for the strong move Geller found here, but for its background story. This game was played at the 1955 Interzonal tournament in Gothenburg. The line was not only prepared by Panno, but by the whole Argentinian team and it happened to appear not only on this board, but also in the games Keres-Najdorf and Spassky-Pilnik in the very same round. The soviet players only had to copy Geller's brilliant idea to score 3 points on this day. }
13. Bb5
{ The only good move for White. It probably doesn't lead to an advantage, but everything else is just bad for White. }
13... Ne5
{ Pilnik, probably shocked by Geller's novelty, immediately blunders. Much better is   13...Rh7=  and the theoretical debate here is still ongoing today. Black is probably fine. }
14. Bg3
{ and Black is already busted. The game continued with   14...Bxg5  15.O-O+  Ke7  16.Bxe5  Qb6+  17.Kh1  dxe5  18.Qf7+  Kd6  19.Rad1+  and White won quickly. }
*

