[Round "?"]
[White "Legends"]
[Black "Spassky, Boris V vs. Pilnik, Hermann"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq4/1p1kbR2/2npp1Q1/1p6/4P3/2N3B1/PPP3PP/6K1 w - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Welcome back to Gothenburg 1955. The start of the game was the same as Geller-Panno. }
22. Nd5
{ Bringing the last piece into the attack. Now, the main threat is Nxe7 followed by Bh4. }
22... Rxa2
{ 22...exd5  23.Qxd6+  Ke8  24.Qg6  Kd7   24...Be6  25.Qxe6  dxe4  26.Qg6  This line looks more like a game of Nine men's morris than chess.  26...Qd4+  27.Kh1  Nd8  28.Rf6+  Kd7  29.Qf5+  Ke8  30.Qxb5+  Nc6  31.Qh5+  Kd8  32.Rf5+-  25.exd5  Nb4  26.d6+- }
23. h3
{ 23.h4  with the same idea works too, but there is no reason to put the pawn on a vulnerable square.   23.Nxe7  Nxe7  24.Bh4  isn't good enough yet.  24...Kc6  25.Rxe7  Qb6+  26.Kf1  Qe3∓  and suddenly White's king is worse than Black's king. }
23... Ra1+ { 23...Rxb2  24.Kh2+-  followed by Qf6. Black's king can't escape. }
24. Kh2 exd5 25. Qxd6+ Ke8 26. Qg6
{ White wins similarly to the annotations to 22...exd5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Legends"]
[Black "Polgar, Judit vs. Ivanchuk, Vassily"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1q1rr1k1/1p2bp1p/p3n1p1/P1p1P3/6P1/2NB1R1Q/1PP4P/4R2K w - - 0 25"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The best woman to ever play the game, Judit Polgar, was most feared for her amazing attacking skills. Here she showed why against another legendary player. }
25. Ne4 Qxe5 26. Rxf7
{ A common idea in such positions.   26.Nf6+?!  Bxf6  27.Rxe5  Bxe5+= } 26...
Ng5
{ Taking the rook loses quickly.   26...Kxf7  27.Qxh7+  Qg7   27...Ng7  28.Bc4+  Kf8  29.Qh8  28.Rf1+  Bf6  29.Rxf6+  Ke7  30.Rxe6++- }
27. Nxg5 Qxe1+ 28. Bf1 { Not   28.Kg2?  Qd2+  29.Rf2??  Qxg5-+ } 28... h5 29.
Qb3
{ The coup de grace. White's queen finds another route to Black's king. The game continuation }
29... c4
{ led to a nice mating finish.   29...Bxg5  30.Re7+  Kh8  31.Rxe1  Rxe1  32.Qc3++- }
30. Qxc4 Rc8 31. Rf8+ { 31.Qd5  and   31.Qd4  win too. } 31... Kg7
{ 31...Kxf8  32.Qf7 } 32. Qg8+ Kh6 33. Nf7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Legends"]
[Black "Tal, Mihail vs. Tolush, Alexander V"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb1kb1r/1p1n1ppp/p3p3/4P1B1/q2NN3/1R6/2PQ1KPP/5B1R w kq - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We started the chapter with two tactics of the great Mihail Tal, and we end it with one. Here, he is in action in the Poisoned Pawn Variation. You are in for a treat! }
15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. Qxd6
{ First part of the mission accomplished. Black's king is stuck in the center for now. }
17... Rf8+
{ 17...Kf7  18.Qe7+  Kg6  19.Bd3+  Kh5  20.Rb4+-   17...Nc6  18.Qxe6+  Kf8  19.Rf3++- }
18. Kg3
{ 18.Kg1??  Rxf1+  19.Kxf1  Qc4+!  20.Ke1  Nc6-+  All threats are parried and White has no way to refuel his attack. }
18... Nf6
{ 18...Rf7  19.Qxe6+  Kf8  20.Bc4+-   18...Kf7  19.Rf3+  Kg8  20.Qxe6+  Kh8  21.Rxf8+  Nxf8  22.Qxc8+- }
19. exf6 gxf6
{ 19...Qd7  20.Qxd7+!  Nxd7  21.fxg7  Rg8  22.Bh6+-  Here it's not mate for a change, but a won endgame. The passer on g7 will cost Black material. }
20. Be2 { The eye of the storm. White brings another attacker in. } 20... fxg5
{ 20...Nd7  21.Bh5+  Kd8  22.Be3  Qc6   22...Rg8+  23.Kh3+-  23.Bb6+  Qxb6  24.Rxb6+- }
21. Bh5+ Rf7 22. Bxf7+ Kxf7 23. Rf3+ { Of course,  23.Rf1+  works as well. } *

