[Black "Barrientos, S. vs. Nguyen, Anh Khoi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r3rk1/2qbbp1p/3ppnpP/ppn3B1/3NP1P1/PBN2P2/1PPQ4/1K1R3R w - - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

19. Nf5 { The typical can opener in this kind of positions. } 19... gxf5
{ 19...exf5  20.Nd5!  Nxb3  21.Nxe7+  Kh8  22.Bxf6   20...Nxd5  21.Bxe7  Nxe7  22.Qd4+- }
20. Bh4
{ But this brilliant quiet move isn't typical at all. White opens g5 for the queen.   20.gxf5?  Kh8  isn't clear at all.  21.Bh4   21.Qf4  Rg8  22.fxe6  Rxg5  23.Qxg5  Rg8  24.Qe3  fxe6=+  and I'd prefer Black.  Bd8  22.Qd4  e5  23.Qxd6  Qxd6  24.Rxd6  b4= }
20... Kh8 21. Qg5 Rg8 22. Qxf6+ Bxf6 23. Bxf6+
{ White is completely winning. The most beautiful and thematic way to finish the game would be   23...Rg7  24.hxg7+  Kg8  25.Rxh7!  Kxh7  26.exf5  exf5  27.Bxf7  and Rh1+ followed by mate is inevitable. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Brainteasers"]
[Black "Leskovar, Mario Leopoldo vs. Molner, Mackenzie"]
[Result "*"]
