[White "Brainteasers"]
[Black "Moldovan, Daniel vs. Bouaziz, Slim"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1kb1r/3n1p1p/p2ppp2/1p5B/q2NPP2/2P5/P5PP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14. Bxf7+ Kd8
{ 14...Kxf7  15.Qh5+  Ke7  16.Nc6   15...Kg8  16.Qg4+  Kf7  17.Qxe6+  Kg7  18.Nf5+  Kg6  19.Qe8   14...Ke7  15.Qh5  Nc5  16.Be8!  Kd8  17.Qf7  Threatening Nc6#  17...Bb7  18.Nxe6+  Nxe6  19.Qd7 }
15. Nxe6+ Ke7 16. Qh5 Qc4 17. e5
{ White needs to open up more lines against Black's king quickly.   17.Rae1  for example is too slow.  17...Nc5  18.Nd8  Ne6= }
17... dxe5 { 17...fxe5  18.fxe5  Nxe5  19.Qg5+  Kd7  20.Nxf8++- } 18. Rad1
{ The final touch, White brings the last piece into the attack, prevents Black's best freeing try Nc5 and Black is busted. This is again a nice example of what happens to the black king if he doesn't manage to castle and the center opens up. We give a few example variations.   18...Nc5  19.fxe5  Nxe6  20.exf6#  This was the main point of Rad1, Black's king can't run.   18...Qxc3  19.Be8+-   18...Bb7  19.Rxd7+  Kxd7  20.Nxf8++-   18.Rae1?  Nc5  19.fxe5?  Bxe6-+ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Brainteasers"]
[Black "Saathoff, Richard vs. Seyb, Alexander"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1q2kb1r/3b1ppp/Q3pn2/4p1B1/8/2N5/PrP2PPP/2KR1B1R w k - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14. Rxd7 Nxd7 15. Bb5 Rb4
{ 15...Rxb5  is testing as well.  16.Nxb5  h6  After   16...Be7  17.Bxe7  Kxe7  White has to find a funny sequence.  18.Rd1  Nc5  Otherwise Qa3+ is ugly.  19.Qc6  Rc8  20.Na7+-  17.Be3+-  and Black's king won't manage to castle. e.g.  17...Be7   17...Bc5  18.Bxc5  Nxc5  19.Qc6++-  18.Rd1  Nf6  19.Ba7+- }
16. Be3
{ White needs to stop Rd4.   16.Rd1?  Rd4  17.Ne4   17.Bxd7+  Kxd7=  White is running out of attackers and has to be content with a perpetual.  Be7  18.Be3  Rxd1+  19.Kxd1  O-O =  20.Bxd7  Rd8  21.Qc6  Qb1+  22.Ke2  Qxa2  is completely unclear. }
16... Bd6 17. Rd1 Ke7 18. Bxd7
{ Again, the only move.   18.a3  Rd4  19.Bxd4  exd4  20.Rxd4  Nc5=  is again very much unclear. }
18... Kxd7 19. Ba7
{ Less clear is   19.Bc5  Rd4  20.Bxd4  exd4  21.Rxd4  Ke7  22.g3  Rd8±  and there is a lot of work ahead for White. }
19... Qc7 20. a3
{ Finally, after forcing the queen to c7 we want to win the exchange back. }
20... Rd4 21. Bxd4 exd4 22. Rxd4
{ Black is busted. He can't stop Nb5, e.g.   22...Ke7  23.Nb5  Bf4+  24.Kb1  Rb8  25.Qa4!  +-  with the double threat Qb4+ and Rxf4. }
*

